y within many Islamic scholarly platforms (old as well as new); an energy which aims to provide dynamic answers to modern day challenges from within the Islamic legal and theological tradition.Key featuresFocuses on four influential Sunni Islamic scholarly platforms with a global following: Al-Azhar (Egypt); Saudi Salafism (Saudi Arabia); Deoband (South Asia); Diyanet (Turkey)Each case study traces the institution’s intellectual genealogy, contemporary political standing, and the discourses of its scholars on Islamic law and social change  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAuthorityxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aIslam and civil societyzIslamic countries. 0aIslam and civil societyzWestern countries. 0aIslam and culturezIslamic countries. 0aIslam and culturezWestern countries. 0aIslamxDoctrines. 0aIslamy21st century. 0aIslamic sociology. 0aMuslim scholarszIslamic countries. 0aMuslim scholarszWestern countries. 0aTaqlīd. 0aTaqlīd. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aBano, Masooda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaliskan, Emre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRazavian, Christopher Pooya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpannaus, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 apan, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311078043740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147443324240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474433242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474433242/original  a978-3-11-078043-7  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BA